    "markdown": "## Triphase CT Abdomen Overview\n\n## 1. Triphasic CT Abdomen Overview\n### What is a Triphasic CT Scan Abdomen?\nA \\*\\*triphasic CT abdomen\\*\\* is a specialised CT scan that captures three distinct “phases” of blood flow through your abdominal organs after an iodine-based contrast injection. Each phase highlights different blood vessels and tissue characteristics, giving doctors a dynamic view impossible to obtain with routine imaging.\n### How It Differs from Routine CT\n- \\*\\*Routine CT\\*\\*: Single-phase image—good for general anatomy.\n- \\*\\*Triphasic CT\\*\\*: Three timed phases—arterial, portal venous, and delayed—pinpointing tiny tumours, vascular invasion, or subtle lesions.\n---\n## 2. What is Triphasic CT Abdomen?\n### Triple-Phase Imaging Explained\n1. \\*\\*Arterial Phase (20–25 s)\\*\\*: Highlights arteries and hypervascular tumours.\n2. \\*\\*Portal Venous Phase (60–70 s)\\*\\*: Shows organ parenchyma and venous drainage.\n3. \\*\\*Delayed Phase (3–5 min)\\*\\*: Detects contrast wash-out patterns, scarring, or leaks.\n### Radiation & Safety Profile\n- \\*\\*Effective dose\\*\\*: ~5–8 mSv (similar to 1–2 years of natural background).\n- \\*\\*ALARA principle\\*\\*: Lowest dose achievable with iterative reconstruction software.\n- \\*\\*Contrast\\*\\*: Non-ionic, low-osmolar to reduce allergy risk.\n---\n## 3. When and Who Needs Triphasic CT Abdomen?\n### Liver Lesion Characterisation\n- Distinguish benign haemangioma from \\*\\*hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)\\*\\*.\n- Detect tiny hypervascular metastases.\n### Pancreatic & Renal Mass Work-up\n- Evaluate \\*\\*renal cell carcinoma (RCC)\\*\\* extension into veins.\n- Stage \\*\\*pancreatic neuroendocrine tumours\\*\\*.\n### Follow-up After Treatment\n- Post-chemoembolisation or post-surgery assessment of residual tumour.\n\n## Risks & Limitations of Triphase CT Abdomen\n\n### Contrast Allergy Precautions\n- Mild reactions: rash, nausea (1–3 %).\n- Severe anaphylaxis (<0.04 %).\n- \\*\\*Pre-medication\\*\\* available for prior allergy.\n### Renal Function Requirements\n- \\*\\*Serum creatinine ≤1.5 mg/dL\\*\\* (or eGFR ≥45).\n- Hydration protocol for borderline values.\n\n## Parameters Considered During Triphase CT Abdomen\n\n## 5. Types of Triphasic CT Abdomen Protocols\n### Standard Triphasic Liver Protocol\n- Arterial, portal venous, and 3-minute delayed phases centred on liver.\n### Modified Triple-Phase for Kidneys\n- Corticomedullary, nephrographic, and excretory phases to map \\*\\*renal masses\\*\\* and collecting-system anatomy.\n---\n## 6. List of Parameters Considered During Triphasic CT Abdomen\n- \\*\\*Arterial Phase Findings\\*\\*: Arterial enhancement, hypervascular foci.\n- \\*\\*Portal Venous Phase Findings\\*\\*: Lesion wash-out, venous thrombus.\n- \\*\\*Delayed Phase Findings\\*\\*: Capsular retraction, contrast pooling.\n\n## Reasons for Taking a Triphase CT Abdomen\n\n- \\*\\*Detect hypervascular tumours\\*\\* before symptoms appear.\n- \\*\\*Assess vascular invasion\\*\\* (portal vein, renal vein).\n- \\*\\*Guide surgical planning\\*\\* with 3-D vascular mapping.\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Test\n\n- \\*\\*Sub-millimetre resolution\\*\\*: 128-slice CT with 0.625 mm slices.\n- \\*\\*Same-day reporting\\*\\*: Radiologists on-site until 9 p.m.\n- \\*\\*Transparent pricing\\*\\*: No hidden contrast or film charges.\n\n## Illness Diagnosed with Triphase CT Abdomen\n\n- \\*\\*Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Renal cell carcinoma (RCC)\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Neuroendocrine tumours (NETs)\\*\\*\n\n## Preparing for Triphase CT Abdomen\n\n### Fasting & Hydration Guidelines\n- \\*\\*Fast 4–6 h\\*\\* before scan.\n- \\*\\*Drink 500 mL water\\*\\* up to 1 h prior to aid contrast excretion.\n### Medication Adjustments\n- \\*\\*Metformin\\*\\*: Pause 48 h post-scan if eGFR <60.\n- \\*\\*Diabetes\\*\\*: Morning slots preferred for better glycaemic control.\n---\n## 11. Pre-requisites for Triphasic CT Abdomen\n- \\*\\*Recent creatinine report\\*\\* (within 4 weeks).\n- \\*\\*Contrast consent form\\*\\* signed after allergy & renal screening.\n---\n## 12. Best Time to Take Triphasic CT Abdomen\n- \\*\\*Morning slots\\*\\* for diabetic patients to minimise fasting hypoglycaemia.\n- \\*\\*Emergency 24/7 availability\\*\\* for acute abdominal pain or trauma.\n---\n## 13. Eligibility for Triphasic CT Abdomen\n- \\*\\*Adults & seniors\\*\\*: No upper age limit.\n- \\*\\*Pediatric considerations\\*\\*: Tailored low-dose protocols for >5 years; younger children may require anaesthesia.\n---\n## 14. Procedure for Triphasic CT Abdomen at Cadabams\n1. \\*\\*Check-in & vitals\\*\\* (10 min).\n2. \\*\\*IV cannula insertion\\*\\* (18–20 G) in antecubital vein.\n3. \\*\\*Positioning\\*\\* on CT table, arms above head.\n4. \\*\\*Contrast injection\\*\\* (100–120 mL at 4–5 mL/s) with automated injector.\n5. \\*\\*Three-phase scanning\\*\\* (total 5–7 min).\n6. \\*\\*Post-scan observation\\*\\* (15 min for delayed reactions).\n---\n## 15. Caution Before Taking Triphasic CT Abdomen\n- \\*\\*Pregnancy screening\\*\\*: Urine β-hCG for women 12–50 years.\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia support\\*\\*: Open-bore CT & mild sedation on request."
  },
